status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"Each false statement (a)–(e) is corrected by providing the standard counterexample and the precise theorem.\"\n             :formal-name \"b93J01_corrected_statements\"\n             :formal-target \"⟨A_4 has a normal Klein four subgroup; there exist five nonisomorphic groups of order eight (including Z2_cube and Q8); S_3 has no subgroup of order six other than itself, showing the subgroup-divisor claim fails while Sylow guarantees only prime-power orders; the additive group Q is abelian but not a direct sum of cyclic groups, whereas every finitely generated abelian group decomposes into cyclic summands; for primes p<q with p dividing q-1 there is a non-abelian semidirect product of order pq so not every such group is cyclic.⟩\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"Records the explicit counterexamples and corrected formulations demanded in Stage 1.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"b93J01_corrected_statements\"\n              :formal-statement \"⟨A_4 has a normal Klein four subgroup; … ; for primes p<q with p∣(q−1) there is a non-abelian semidirect product of order pq.⟩\"\n              :informal-clause \"Bundles the corrections for parts (a)–(e).\"\n              :role :main-theorem}\n             {:formal-name \"sylow_helper\"\n              :formal-statement \"Sylow and Cauchy theorems supply subgroups corresponding to prime divisors.\"\n              :informal-clause \"Explains the fix for part (c).\"\n              :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\n- drafted the full reader-facing solution plus study-notes scaffolding in `execute.md`; the write-up now includes the traps, key idea, the detailed fixes for (a)–(e), and the “what connects” crib sheet.\n- refreshed the machine-readable plan (`proof-plan.edn`) and the alignment (`formal-alignment.edn`) so the counterexample strategy and the new Lean lemmas (`Examples.sym3_not_isCyclic`, `Examples.card_sym3`, `Examples.card_zmod2_cubed`) are explicitly recorded for target-check.\n- implemented the corresponding Lean witnesses in `ApmCanaries/Frames/B93J01/Apm_v2_b93J01_1775006040768/Main.lean` and checked them with `lake build` (clean run; only unrelated global warnings remain).\n- updated the frame changelog to log Stage 1/2 completions and the in-progress Lean stage.\n\n**Why it’s hard.** Every bullet echoes a correct theorem but quietly omits a hypothesis: the simplicity of \\(A_n\\) needs \\(n\\ge5\\), the order‑8 classification has five (not three) types, Sylow’s theorem guarantees only prime-power subgroups, the structure theorem holds only for finitely generated abelian groups, and groups of order \\(pq\\) are cyclic precisely when \\(p\\nmid(q-1)\\). Missing those caveats leaves you with no counterexample at exam time.\n\n**Key insight.** For each claim, find the smallest obstruction: \\(A_4\\) contains the normal Klein four; \\(Q_8\\) and \\((\\Bbb Z/2)^3\\) finish the order‑8 catalogue; \\(A_4\\) again has no subgroup of order 6; divisible abelian groups like \\(\\Bbb Q\\) or Prüfer \\(p\\)-groups are not direct sums of cyclics; \\(S_3\\) (order \\(2\\cdot3\\)) is non-cyclic because \\(2\\mid (3-1)\\).\n\n**Complete proof (reader-facing, in `execute.md`).**\n- **(a)** Exhibit the normal Klein four \\(V\\le A_4\\) to refute “\\(A_n\\) simple for all \\(n\\ge3\\)” and state the correct theorem: \\(A_3\\cong C_3\\) is simple, and \\(A_n\\) is simple exactly for \\(n\\ge5\\).\n- **(b)** Add the missing order‑8 groups: the elementary abelian \\((\\Bbb Z/2)^3\\) (all elements of order 2) and the quaternion group \\(Q_8\\). The corrected classification: \\(\\Bbb Z/8\\), \\(\\Bbb Z/4\\oplus\\Bbb Z/2\\), \\((\\Bbb Z/2)^3\\), \\(D_4\\), \\(Q_8\\).\n- **(c)** In \\(A_4\\) (order 12), any index‑2 subgroup would be normal yet every normal subgroup sits inside \\(V\\), so there’s no subgroup of order 6 despite \\(6\\mid12\\). The valid replacement is Sylow/Cauchy: only prime-power divisors are guaranteed subgroups.\n- **(d)** \\(\\Bbb Q\\) (and Prüfer \\(p\\)-groups \\(\\Bbb Z_{p^\\infty}\\)) are abelian but not direct sums of cyclic groups because of unbounded divisibility. State the actual structure theorem: every *finitely generated* abelian group splits as a direct sum of cyclics.\n- **(e)** Take \\(S_3\\) (order \\(2\\cdot3\\)): it’s non-abelian, hence non-cyclic. In general, a group of order \\(pq\\) with \\(p<q\\) is cyclic iff \\(p\\nmid(q-1)\\); otherwise a non-abelian semidirect product \\(\\Bbb Z/q\\rtimes\\Bbb Z/p\\) exists.\n\n**Lean 4 formalization (in `Main.lean`).**\n- `Examples.card_sym3` proves \\(|S_3|=6\\) by evaluating \\(3!\\).\n- `Examples.sym3_not_isCommutative` and `Examples.sym3_not_isCyclic` formalize the part-(e) obstruction: two transpositions in \\(S_3\\) fail to commute, so the group is not cyclic.\n- `Examples.card_zmod2_cubed` captures the missing order‑8 type by showing \\((\\Bbb Z/2)^3\\) has eight elements (supporting part (b)’s catalogue).\n- Build status: `lake build` completed successfully (only unrelated global linter warnings about unused variables in other modules remain).\n- Still open on the Lean side: formalizing the normal-subgroup analysis for \\(A_4\\), the absence of order‑6 subgroups in \\(A_4\\), and the non–finitely-generated abelian counterexamples; those are documented in Stage 3.\n\n**What connects / exam-day field kit.**\n1. *Alternating groups*: remember \\(A_4\\)’s normal Klein four and that simplicity kicks in only from \\(n=5\\).\n2. *Finite groups of small order*: know all five order‑8 types and that \\((\\Bbb Z/2)^3\\) is the unique exponent‑2 model.\n3. *Sylow scope*: only prime powers are guaranteed; arbitrary divisors need not occur (classic counterexample \\(A_4\\)).\n4. *Abelian structure*: “direct sum of cyclics” ⇔ “finitely generated”—watch for divisible groups.\n5. *Order \\(pq\\) groups*: cyclic iff \\(p\\nmid(q-1)\\); otherwise the semidirect product (and \\(S_3\\)) saves the day.\n\nLet me know if you’d like the remaining Lean pieces (A4’s normal subgroup lattice, Prüfer/Q formalization) pushed through next.", :frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/B93J01/Apm_v2_b93J01_1775006040768", :frame/id "apm-v2-b93J01-1775006040768", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :workspace/generated-at "2026-04-01T01:14:00.792325Z", :frame/shared-extension-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Local", :frame/module-root "ApmCanaries.Frames.B93J01.Apm_v2_b93J01_1775006040768", :proof/problem-id "b93J01", :workspace/schema "proof-frame-workspace.v1", :frame/workspace-root "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/b93J01/apm-v2-b93J01-1775006040768", :artifacts {:proof-plan "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/b93J01/apm-v2-b93J01-1775006040768/proof-plan.edn", :formal-alignment "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/b93J01/apm-v2-b93J01-1775006040768/formal-alignment.edn", :changelog "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/b93J01/apm-v2-b93J01-1775006040768/changelog.edn", :execute-notes "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/b93J01/apm-v2-b93J01-1775006040768/execute.md", :workspace-readme "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/b93J01/apm-v2-b93J01-1775006040768/README.md", :workspace-metadata "/home/joe/code/futon6/.state/proof-frames/b93J01/apm-v2-b93J01-1775006040768/workspace.json", :lean-main "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/B93J01/Apm_v2_b93J01_1775006040768/Main.lean", :lean-scratch "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/B93J01/Apm_v2_b93J01_1775006040768/Scratch.lean"}}, :artifacts ["/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/B93J01/Apm_v2_b93J01_1775006040768/Main.lean" "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/B93J01/Apm_v2_b93J01_17750